Found in hospital - resources still activated; due to misinformation re location of missing person. [Set dist=0.05]
Person suffering dementia, wandered away from home, found in bus shelter. Had caught a bus. [Presumably found by car patrol.]

MP an English tourist, became disoriented after walking daughters home frm McDonalds. Made no atempt to seek help until 08:30 2-2-2005 after being lost for 14hrs - asked home owner who called police. Travelled approx 12km in many directions on main roads.
Was seated on a log in thick bush & camouflaged by clothing. Dehydrated & minor cuts. Exhausted and immobile due to age and exposured to elements. MP located by Helicopter in heavy bush.
MP in company with a dog short term memory loss not diagnosed with Alzhemiers / Dementia
Disoriented at night gained entry to motor room - he'd been there for 3 nights. Became disoriented enroute to the toilet block. [Put dist at 100m since within caravan park.]
MP known to wander, recently gets disoriented.  Found by local resident confused, disoriented; lying down with hat, shoes, and glasses off.
MP located early May 2005. [t approx 2100 hrs., though presumably dead long before that.]

SAR requested to search for a missing elderly male with Alzheimer's in the Dallas Road area. Members were stood down when the subject was located uninjured by a member of the public. Victoria Police boat, 2 Coast Guard Auxiliary boats, 1 RCMP helicopter and the Beacon Bus aided in search.

A 76 year old male with severe case of Alzheimers went walking from his home, which is a ranch in a rural wilderness setting. SAR Management support from BVSAR was requested by Burns Lake SAR as they did not have one available. ECC contacted SAR Manager Whitney NUMAN to provide SAR Management support, and he in turn tasked Harold DYKSTRA of BVSAR to lead the task. PEP Air was dispatched by SAR Manager to search the area from the air and they located the client and communicated the coordinates to the ground SAR team. The ground SAR team responded to the coordinates and located the client and returned him to his home. BC Ambulance attended the home and following an assessment found the client to be in a good enough condition to remain at home.
Victoria SAR requested by Oak Bay Police to search for missing elderly female with Alzheimer's. Stood down when the subject was located walking in the area by police.

NSR requested by RCMP to search for a patient suffering from Alzheimer's that went missing from his residence in the Norgate area. Search was stood down when the subject was located alive and well by RCMP, the subject was walking the streets about 2 1/2 miles from his home.

70 year male last seen at 14:00 at his home. Wife contacted neigbour at approximately 19:00 that the male subject had not been seen since 14:00. Neighbours searched around the home area and roadways without success. ALSAR contacted by first neighbour. She was advised to contact RCMP. RCMP contacted ALSAR at 20:20. Pagers actived, members responded to Firehall. Members drove to Burton School where command was set up. Command vehicle was parked out side for radio relay. Road search teams were set up and briefed. At 24:15 teams were sent out to do road searches. As teams were leaving RCMP got call that subject had just arrived home. He had become disoriented and was lost but found his way out. Search deactived, members returned to Firehall.

Keremeos SAR responded to search for an 83 yr old male with Alzheimer's missing from his residence overnight. Oliver SAR, Nicola Valley SAR and PEP Air also responded to assist in search efforts. Teams were stood down when the subject was located alive and well in Merritt, he left his home following an argument and chose not to return. Task concluded.

Arrowsmith SAR responded to search for an Alzheimer's patient that walked away from his home at Craig Bay Estates in Parksville. Hasty teams were sent to high probability areas, local residents also helped with search. Search was stood down when the subject was located by a nurse coming from work that knew him. A SAR member was sent with the subject's wife to pick him up and bring him home.

Central Okanagan Regional District SAR members responded to search for a 77 yr old male that suffers from dementia and wandered away from his family campsite at Brown Lake. Members were stood down upon arrival at their staging area as the subject was located by police. Police proceeded to transport the subject to hospital for medical assessment.

Surrey SAR was called by the Surrey RCMP to assist in locating a missing alzhiemers patient. Surrey SAR requested CFV SAR to assist in the process of searching it was discovered she had gotten in a cab and headed to a past residence. The subject was located there and the search was stood down.

Alzeimers sufferer went for a walk & became lost & disoriented.  Reported missing by family members.  Located 1.5kms from home - lost & disoriented on Main Road Stoke at Stoke Mobile Service Station (found by member of public). This is the 5th time in past month this man has done this.  Family told NOT to let him go walking alone & to ensure someone accompanies him at ALL times when he goes walking (which he does every night).
The missing man was last seen near his room at 1840hrs.  He was told to get  into his room and get his walker before he fell over.  He was not

Elderly alzeimers sufferer goes missing from home address.  Police informed by husband but patrols and police dog fail to locate her.  Sar operation put into place with confinement, roving mobile patrols and property by property search radiating from PLS.  Subsequently located in  a property some 250m from home.  Claimed to have been at a dance and was waiting for hubby to pick her up!!

73 yr old male  suffer from dementia left in care of rest home while family  away for w/e.  while caregiver at countdown shopping  subject got out of car and wandered off.  located at home address.  Would need a ride from member of public to get there as incapable of walking any distance.  carries id bracelet with name and home address.   Staff notifed and plan of search begun when subject located by caregiver.

The 65 year missing dementia afflicted woman had been seated in a motor vehicle outside a plumbing shop near the centre of Invercargill. her husband has entered the shop for approx 5 mins and returned at aorund 1515hours and the woman had left the vehicle. he carried out his own search of surrounding streets and greenbelts for approx 1 hour with no luck. he contacted police and all dairies, service stations and taxis were notified expecting early recovery with a negative result. SAR management etc notified when darkness had fell and the search was coordinated correctly at that stage (it was slightly late and has been addressed with local S/Sgts). A full search was commenced using targetting of area of porobability within 500ms of last known point included a number of physical barriers which the missing party was deemed to not have crossed.The missing party walked out to  service station from a green belt - bush area and was in good spirits. the direction she was noted coming from was  an area that search teams were working through. Her condition is such that it was impossible to ascertain where she had wandered or parked up. It was rather unusal that this woman could remain mobile for 7 hours without being spotted. D/Sgt mcphail spoke to husband to confirm there was no possibility (medical examination) of someother factor ( criminal act) being present but appears 
negative. WELL THOUGHT OUT SEARCH PLAN BY NZLANDSAR MANAGEMENT

victim lives with husband at address for past 30 years. Has suffered mild dementia for the past 4 years. Has wondered off 2 other times recently but has  been located early on. At 15:30 hours victim stated that she was going to the local butcher to get meat for dinner and left. Husband phoned 2 hours laterafter believing he had to wait 2 hours. pOlice called at 17:50 hours it was starting to get dark. Eagle called and SAR squad about to be paged when a possible sighting in mangere (next suburb) . Victim located by myself at mangere shopping centre.
Spoke with victim had good long term memory knew her street address and phone number but thought she was with her husband and confused why I was taking her home .. Was wearing an ID bracelet for this reason but it was not used.

Had no short term memory or concept of time. Did not like answering questions. 

At home did not know how she got home or where she had been. Was on medication 

but had bad side effects and was no longer taking it.

Very fit as she walked everyday. I believe the reason she was located was 

because she came to a shopping centre or would have kept on 

walking

Subject is an Alzheimers sufferer who has previously gone missing, often located nearby.  On this occasion he walked quite a distance(8 km), across  Mangere Bridge.  He went missing at about 2030 on 09.09.03, but Police were not notified until 0330hrs 10.09.03. Located by members of the public at 339 Neilson Street, Onehunga, NZ Rail Ltd at 06:45hrs.

The missing man went from Elizabeth Memorial Hospital. It was reported that he  was a type 2 diabetic, and can be aggressive and violent.  He has schitzophernia and dementia.  The mood he was in could have made him go walkabout.  Information from Train control that a male was on the Kaiwharawhara platform was checked and it was the misisng man. He was returned to the hospital.
Informants mother went missing from home.  She was located a short time later  at the St Kilda church.  She previously had been located at the parade Island  Bay another time.

Elderly person suffering chest pains went for a walk after being upset by 

wife.  Didn't come home, Located in school grounds sheltering from rain



Log

HUGHES has just been released from Wellington Hospital Emergency Depatment for 

an unknown condition. He wandered off before his daughter arrived to collect 

him. No major concerns/med problems/ formal dementia - just disorientated. 

Local police units and daughter checked area. SAR squad O'CONNELL & DAVIES 

involved in investigation phase when HUGHES located in Paraparaumu by 

son-in-law. Had taken bus and train then called son-in-law for a lift home.

Subject admitted to "secure' resthome on afternoon of 19 November after being 

in respite care at Princess Margaret Hospital (no longer able to look after 

himself) he was seen at the home at about 2100hrs and noticed missing about 

2113hrs and reported to Police at 2143hrs.  Police staff and dog handler sent 

to the scene in a residental suburb of Christhchurch.  Police SAR Co-ordinator 

contacted at 2300hrs and advice given re search areas, techniques (dogs, check 

resthome (again), chech paths and bush ares within 1 km of PLS) searchers 

activated midnigh when nothing located.  riefing at new Brighton Police Station 

0045hrs and staff tasked to search 4 areas - creeks and waterways, golfcourse, 

and adjacent areas.  Identified a mean search area of about 1 km diameter.  

Dogs deployed to high probability areas.  Report received at about 0220hrs of a 

male person fitting description in the Avondale area - confused elderly male 

walking along Breezes Road.  Police staff working on the search responded and 

located subject in Breezes Road near Cardrona Street - in response he said that 

he was going to 264 Opawa Road (former home).  Had had a fall 'half way round'  

Unaware of the time he had ben walking.  

Analysis is that the subject walked out of the insecure ;secure; rest home, 

trued right onto Horseshoe lake Road, left onto New Brighton road and followed 

that road, crossed the Avondale Road Bridge and walked up Avondale Road where 

he wasseen by a baker at the Avondale Shops - informant rang Police and subject 

located and returned to the rest home (now complete with nailed shut gates!) - 

daugher informed and she travelled to the unit.

Went missing from a large rest home . staff took several hours to contact 

police SAR called gave advice and wanted basics completed b4 squad deployed . 

Person sighted by member of the public located 1.8 km from the home . Likely 

direction of travel is back to her old home address as she had only been in the 

rest home for a few days

Elderly visitor to Wellington was visiting family and told them he wanted to go 

for a walk for about an hour. He decided to return to the place he was staying 

in Lower Hutt. He made his way to Wellington Railway Station but took a train 

to Johnsonville by mistake.

After Police reported his description to Cab companies, a taxi driver reported 

seening him in Johnsonville.



Police returned him safely to his family.

Elderly Demetia patient wandered away from Wesley Care Rest Home. Has 

previuosly wandered from the home which is her permanent residence. Fears held 

for her safety as she has made mention of walkling into the sea at Lyall Bay.



Physical health is fine but has no concept of direction or distance travelled.



After her description was broadcast on Polce radio, a member located her in the 

city.

TWICE A DAY SUBJECT GOES WALKING THROUGH MT EDEN. USUALLY SITS ON A CHAIR AT 

THE TOP AND READS HIS NEWSPAPER.

THIS OCCASSION ON AFTERNOON WALK SUBJECT DID NOT RETURN . FAMILY SPENT 5 HOURS 

LOOKING FOR HIM BEFORE CONTACTING POLICE.SAR DEPLOYED IN MT EDEN AND LOCATED 

HIM OFF A TRACK STATIONARY. SAR TEAM HEARD A NOISE (MOVEMENT NOT VOICE) WHICH 

ATTRACTED THEM TO SUBJECT . SUBJECT COULD NOT SPEAK ENGLISH BUT WAS PLEASED TO 

SEE POLICE BY GIVING THUMBS UP AND SMILING. WOULD NOT GO WITH POLICE TO LEAVE 

AREA HAD TO BRING DAUGHTER IN TO GET HIM OUT IN EXPLANATION IN CHINA POLICE 

TAKE AWAY BAD PEOPLE AND HE WAS NOT A BAD PERSON. ALL ENDED SUCCESSFULLY

On the 31.01.04 WATT was with a group of intellectually impaired people who 

were visiting Arrowtown.  While at the Skateboard ramp he disappeared and the 

group looked for him but were unable to locate him.



Police searched Arrowtown during the evening and night but could not locate 

him.  Foot search was conducted by Wakatipu Volunteers on 01.02.04.



WATT came to the Police stationat approx 1800 on 01.02.04 having found a 

hubcap.  Claimed he felt like walking to Glenorchy and had slept the night on 

the beach, unknown where.



SAR Advisor Russell Carr

84 Year old, suffers from mild dementia.  Has wandered on at least 4 occasions 

in the past.  Left by family at Old Papatoetoe Shops for 1.5 hours and failed 

to make pick up.   Expected to catch a taxi home as in the past and did not.   

Police notified at 2050 hrs.   SAR contacted for advice, matter handled by 

local staff, due to SAR being involved with another matter. Located by neice on 

Bridge Street, sitting on a seat 24 hours later.  No harm.

64 year old suffering from Dementia.  Recent immigrant from USA.  Went 

walkabout, wandered from Henderson to Albany, a very long distance.  SAR 

contacted for advice, dealt with by local staff

Dementia Patient.  Seen by staff of rest home sitting at bus stop near rest 

home at 1900hrs .  They went back an hour later to get her and she had gone. On 

previous occasion has wandered, and caught a bus into Auckland City.  Located 

on this occasion at 0335hrs in Westhaven , Auckland City, after apprently 

catching a bus again.   SAR consulted, matter dealt with at local level  

without callout of SAR Staff.

Missing Party is a regular walkaway.  She has suffered increasing dementia in 

the past 9 months with frequent bouts of wandering.  On this occasion she went 

for a walk around the block and was not seen again.  Spent the night out, 

unknown location.  SAR activated in morning.  Search commenced to clear high 

risk areas and attempt to locate.  Found by family friend in pub in Pakuranga.  

Had been sleeping on couch,but bar staff had not thought to call Police.  When 

located she was found to be suffering from severe dementia, but otherwise 

unharmed. Has no recollection of what she had been doing or where she had 

been.

Lost party arrived in area with two others with the intention of walking up the 

track to the Kaite Falls. Due to the steepness of the track the other two in 

the party returned to carpark. Lost party continues.

Lost party following track. Female losses balance and falls down bank dragging 

husband with her. Not able to climb back up onto track due to steepness.

Lost party followed river for a short period. Realised that they were lost and 

remained in that position until located.



Search method: Tracks all check prior to the arrival of SAR squad by Police and 

locals. Not located. Due to age and medical concerns of lost party urgent 

response required. Helicopter dispatched to scene. Lost party located in river 

bed. Nil injuries



Debrief: Held after search. Nothing of interest. Area easily contained. Only 

concern is that any tracks were destroyed by locals searching in the first 

instant. This cannot be avoided and must expect that this will happen given 

circumstances.

77 yr old male suffering form Dementia became disoriented on one of his regular 

walks in scrubby marshland near his home in a reitement village. It appears he 

diverted off a well-used track - one he uses himself every day - for reasons 

unknown.



Rest home staff were unable to locate him in the usual areas he frequents. SAR 

Police dog searched scrub off track, indicated one area on track, but nil 

located by handler. Search teams conducted sound sweep after dog had finished, 

located missing male in general area where dog had indicated. 



Team members heard him "mumbling" to himself. He did not respond to voice 

appeal. The team followed the direction of the mumbling and located him sitting 

in a pudlle approx 70-80 metres in scrub, partially disrobed.

Elderly male suffering from memory loss and Parkinsons Disease went wandering 

from his rest home at 1300hrs.  Reported at 1500hrs.  He suffered from a number 

of medical conditions and required medication.  Area patrols and enquiries by 

GDB staff failed to locate hims.  SAR activated at 0645 the next day.  



At about 0830hrs he was located by a homeowner lying down the bottom of a 

bank.  It would appear the person had wandered along the road, and stumbled 

down the bank where he probably lay most of the night, until discovered that 

morning.



Ambulance called and he was recovered by stretcher.  Taken to hospital for 

treatment.  Vey lucky to be alive, a pretty tough old boy.

Lost person suffers from Dementia/alzhiemers. At 1400hrs taken to Rest Home for 

respite care by her husband. Rest home not advised of her condition. She 

wandered off after about an hour and had walked about 3km to the grave of a 

deceased son then headed towards her home. Located near her home, but 1km away 

from Rest home. Alzheimer field worker contacted and co-opted into search. She 

had advised that the cemetary (where lost person had been ) was a likely 

destination......Note these Field workers are a very useful resource.

83 YEAR OLD ALZHIMERS SUFFERER WANDERED OFF FROM REST HOME INTO BUSH RESERVE 

AREA NEAR BY.  LOCATED AT THE REAR OF AN ADDRESS NEAR THE MAUNU RESERVE BY SAR 

SQUAD.

Subject taken for walk by her daughter, grandson and daughters friend. 

About 150m from car they climbed a sandhill . Subject decided it would be too 

far to go out to surf so she headed back while others went on.  All were to 

meet at car. 

When others arrived back at car later she wasn't there.  After their own brief 

search Daughter called Police. 

Subject headed East initially then , following easiest path on sandhill, curved 

South, West, then North.  Subject then followed a path through the sandhills 

becoming steadily more disorientated until found.

Elderly female suffering from Alzheimer's wandered away while at the Waitakiri 

Golf Course. Rural setting with large plantation and walking tracks surrounding 

it. She eventually arrived at her house having walked back. No medical 

problems.

Subject walked away from caregiver at the Whanagrei RSA after having a meal 

there. Caregiver was paying for the meal when the subject left the building. 

Subject suffers from dementia. Police conducted mobile and footpatrols in and 

around the city area. Library and local park next to RSA also checked. Subject 

located by member of the public in a confused and distressed state at the 

Tikipunga shopping area some 4km from PLS.(Subject would have covered this 

distance in 2 hours). Subject has walked in a Northerly direction by following 

the main route into and out of town ( virtually a straight line).

72 year old alzhiemers suffers wanders off from home.  search delayed several 

hours due to not being reported and sar staff invovled in 1w at cape egmont.  

subject loctaed by security guard in industrial area

80 year old Whitmore suffers from heart condition and dementia. Walks out of 

rest home and is located lying ina ditch a few hundred metres from the rest 

home. Returned and given first aid.

Subject lives at home with his caregiver.  He disappeared from home late on 

evening of 22.12.03 and was reported missing at miday on 23.12.03.   A search 

was done and he was found in the Wharekai at the Hirangi Marae later that 

day..  He had gone into the building but could not find his way out.  Good use 

of TCA by search teams.

Subject was having lunch with her caregiver at the RSA , Rust avenue, 

Whangarei. Wandered off while caregiver was paying for there meal. Initial 

search by care giver and members of rhe RSA failed to locate subject.SAR NCO 

called and organised local Police units to conduct search of surrounding area 

while background enquires conducted.



Subject had in the past visited friends in the Tikipunga area and she has a 

daughter living in that area. Mobile patrols sent to Tikipunga to canvas area. 

Subject located near Tikipunga shops safe and well.



 She had walked in excess of 5kms in the two hours she had been missing 

including climbing a large hill. By back tracking from her located position it 

was virtually a straight line by road back to PLS. Route taken was almost 

entirely major roads within the city.

Subject reported missing by her husband. Subjecthad not reurned from a walk, 

usually walks around the block. Suffers from Dementia. Normally only walks for 

10 - 15 minutes. SAR NCO contacted and advised Police patrols to be mobile in 

the area as well as going to address to do initail search of the property. 

Subject located on Howhare avenue approx 1km from her home address. Subject was 

walking along footpath. Safe and well.

At about 2015 hrs on 11/06/04  a  71 year old man was reported missing ffrom 

his rest home.  subject was described as being in the advanced stages of 

dementia and had a history of hiding from staff at the rest home.  



a search was carried out during the night of the rest home and surrounding 

areas.  the subject was not located.  the search was stood down about 0400 hrs 

and begun again at 0700.  



a further search of the rest home at this time found the subject on the roof 

having fallen over a small fence at the top of a set of steps.



subject was taken to hospital suffering from the cold

BURTON was in medical ward at the Taranaki Base Hospital.  At 0142 hours he 

walked out of the hospital.  Concerns due to his mental state and confusion 

from the drugs he is on for a heart condition.  Was missing for some time.  SAR 

personnel were beginning to be called out when BURTON was located near the 

laundry area of the hospital.

Elderly male in rest home suffers from dementia and schizophenia . Goes missing 

very regularly and wanders in all directions. 1st time SAR has been called in . 

Searched during the night. completed media and taxi alerts picked up by member 

of the public on the 14th at Howe St . Was in a distressed state . Was wearing 

a name badge with the rest home details on it . Apart from wandering on a 

regul;ar basis shows no pattern in his wandering apart from staying on roads . 

Can walk very quickly

HARPUR suffering from dementure went for a walk in the Tuatapere Domain and 

fell into a waterway. Due to his health and the depth of the water and mun 

HARPUR was unable to get himself out.

(90 year old suffering from dementia, wandered off from family address at 

approx. 1600 hrs. Reported missing by NOK at 1800 hrs.Missiing party located 

wandering in sanddunes completly disorientated.Returned to NOK.

It was believed that the above person Brathwaite went missing rom the rest home 

at approx 1400hrs, police were not notified until 1730hrs. SArR notified 

at1830hrs, a possible sighting was made near the railway lines at Wairaki Road, 

SAR advisor activated, transrail advised for caution and slower speeds, taxis 

advised, media advised, Police SAR quad paged, SAR dogs paged, a civilian SAR

65 year old alzhiemers patient wanders off from home.  family search for about 

two and a half hours before contacting police 



subject knocks on a residents door while search teams being assembled and 

occupant brings subject to the police station due to her bizarre behaviour



subject travels approximately seven kilometres from where she left

Alzheimer patient missing from Rest Home. Concerns for safety etc. Search 

commenced. Located by a member of the public wandering around streets.To be 

reassessed by Alzheimer field worker for placement into a secure unit.

Subject only been in NZ since June . in 1974 had a head injury resulting in 

short and mid term memory loss although still knew his family . memory loss 

similar to dementia. was walking from he son inlaws house to his house (400m) 

and did not make it to his house. Continued on walking and crossed roads ( 

family said he was not sure how to cross busy roads but would follow other 

pedestrians crossing. Family normally escorts subject when walking but this 

time he left while wife was locking up house. distance from LKP is 4.5 km but 

he would have walked a lot further as he had to go a round a large creek. Found 

by a bus driver in the area 15 minutes after he had been spoken to by police 

SAR and shown a picture

Brook/ Lyn suufered from Dementia. walked off from brother who then notified 

police when he had not returned. Brook has wandered around and taken a fall of 

a steep bank at the rear of a locals property. landed on beach below. corroners 

report says that he drowned. possibly on incoming tide. Broken ribs.

Elderly male reported missing by his son, who had not been in contact with him 

for a couple of days.  Search of immediate area and hospitals etc failed to 

locate him.  SAR activated, whilst on route located by member of the public in 

Orewa , safe and well.

Elderly lady reported missing from rest home at 2100hrs, police informed at 

0200hrs.  Section staff conducted search of premises, not located, SAR 

activated.  Subject located in boiler room of rest home, where she had walked 

herself and door shut behind her.  Safe and well and warm.

78 year old lady , slight dementia, living with neice.  They had an argument , 

she walked out and was not seen again.  SAR activated at 0130hrs.  Search of

SAR received a mutual aid page for assistance in the continuing search for a missing adult in the Mariposa area near Yosemite. The subject (an 80 year old gentleman) had been missing since April 21st, and additional search teams and dog handlers were asked to assist in a full one day search on Saturday, April 30th. A team of four and one area search dog were deployed from Santa Barbara on Friday night, and stayed overnight in Mariposa. On Saturday morning the team was split up into three different teams. Two SAR team members and the search dog formed one team. The other two team members were split up and each accompanied a dog handler from another SAR team or from CARDA. All team members started from the same location, but had different assignments in different areas. Conditions and terrain differed for each team. Weather was accomodating. Teams completed their assignments between 4:30 - 6:30 pm, and were released from the incident following a debrief with Operations. We did not locate the subject. The team travelled back to Santa Barbara that evening, arriving home before midnight.Jennifer, Juanita, Mike W. and Jenna w/ Wyatt.

They will be staying at the Comfort Inn Maricopa.

Should be home Saturday night around midnight.

On 8/23, at 10:00 am, Juanita received a page for Mutual Aid and the request for a Trailing Dog to a search in Buttonwillow, CA for a missing 77 year old gentleman suffering from Alzheimers, and diabetes. The subject was reported missing the day before at approximately 10:00 am. We arrived at the CP at approximately 14:30 and were deployed to a truck stop approximately 3.5 miles away, to a location that a restaurant owner had said he had seen the subject the day before, sitting in the corner of the parking lot. We joined an Area dog team and at the location we interviewed the restaurant owner. He pointed out the location where he said he saw the subject. We searched the area, and Blaze did not give a definitive "on scent" at the location, or in any of the surrounding locations. We searched the truck stop and adjoining parking lot areas, gas stations, etc. We were contacted at approximately 17:30 the missing subject had been located. We returned to the CP. 



The subject was found approximately 700 feet from his residence, deceased.

On 24 July 07 at 2150 hours Clackamas County Sheriffs Office received a call from Molalla PD stating that they had a missing 74 y/o dementia type female missing from Pheasant Point Assisted Living.  Clackamas County Sheriff's search and rescue coordinators start the investigation and search for the missing female. All areas with in the area were covered with no other leads and a meeting was called by the Police Chief of Molalla on day three.  In the meeting we covered all clues and areas searched, SAR coordinators also talked with Sheriff Roberts of the situation.  The Chief of Molalla called off Clackamas County Sheriff's part in the search and was going to leave the search open for his officers.  [Recovery mission 2010-1159.]

Baker County Sheriff Search and Rescue team was activated by Sheriff Southwick on April 13th 2009 around 2230 hours.  We responded to the area on the Snake River between Huntington and Richland.  An 85 year old man with some dementia was reported missing.  He was with a group that parked on the Snake River Road to go fishing and he did not want to hike down to the River from the road.  He stayed in the area of the pickup according to the other members of the group.  They could see him from the fishing spot at times on the road.  They returned to the pickup to find that [subject] was not around.  They searched the area for him and then decided to go for help.  They called 911 from a residence on the Snake River Road.  We responded and did a quick search of the immediate area in the dark.  We then sent two teams out to search along the road.  One team went two miles by truck and parked to walk back toward the point last seen.  The other team started walking from the PLS in the opposite direction.  The downriver team reported by radio they heard a faint "hello" from the steep canyon slope above the road.  We sent additional help to that area but kept the other team on task until the identity was confirmed.  Searchers climbed the steep canyon slope toward the occasional "hello" and found him about 1000 vertical feet above the road.  Once [subject] was located the remaining search members responded to the area with blankets, heat packs and the Stokes basket.  We carried [subject] down the slope to the road to meet the ambulance.  He was transferred to Huntington Ambulance and the team was demobilized.

On April 23, 2009 at about 16:42, Dep. J. Crecelius was advised by Sgt. Alexander that a participant in the Project Lifesaver program had been reported as missing.  Project Lifesaver is a program that is designed for patients that have dementia, autism, or any other condition that may cause the person to become disoriented, lost, and unable to care for themselves.  Project Lifesaver is administered by the Washington County Sheriffs Office.  Dispatch advised Dep. J. Crecelius that caregiver was reporting that [subject] had just left the care facility.  Dep. J. Crecelius responded to the call as a Search and Rescue (SAR) coordinator along with Deputy C. Crecelius.  While on our way to the location we were advised by dispatch that the subject had returned home.  SAR continued to the house to check on [subject] and interview the caregiver.

[subject] is a client of Project Lifesaver, SAR was activated and we attempted to locate the subject by his Project Lifesaver transmitter bracelet. Project Lifesaver client left residence and disabled house alarm around 0630.  He left in a t-shirt and pants on foot.  He has been known to try to walk back to his homeland of Austria. On 7-26-09 at about 1115 hours, Deputies responded regarding a missing 80 year old female.  [Subject] and has been diagnosed with Alzheimer's and Dementia and takes medication several times a day.  [Subject] left the house and was heard saying she wanted to go into the woods and never come back.  [Subject] left out the front door and her husband tried to find her about one minute after she left but was unsuccessful.  [Subject] left in about 90 plus degree weather.  Command post was set up at her residents and multiple Deputies responded and looked around the property, nearby roads and searched with a boat at a nearby lake.  A Patrol tracking K9 responded and conducted a check of the property and outbuildings. [Subject] was checked by medical staff and released back to her family without injury.  SAR Coordinators were stood down as they were arriving on scene with SAR Trucks, trailer and other equipment to set up the Search Base.  Mtn Wave Communication and Search one K9 teams were responding and disregarded after she was located.

On Oct. 20, 2009 Clatsop County Search & Rescue personnel responded to Seaside, OR to assist in the search of an 85 year old male subject that had walked away from an assisted living center.  It was learned that the subject suffered from Alzheimer's and dementia and walked with a shuffle step from a past stroke.  The woods and neighborhood surrounding the assisted living center were searched with negative results.  After searching for several hours the search was suspended at 0430 hours.  Searching resumed at 0700 hours and by 0800 hours the subject was located by a citizen in a nearby neighborhood.  The subject was found in good health and spirits.

Locate a 75 year old male walk away.  Found OK and returned to his wife.

Three men decided to go to the Rusty Butte area up the Sixes River into the National Forest to hike into a mining claim.  There were two brothers and one son of one of the brothers.  Their intentions were to hike down into the drainage to a mining claim they had not been to in several years and then continue to hike down the South Fork of the Sixes River to the Sixes River Campground.  They came to an area where it was not possible to continue.  The younger of the three men decided to hike back out and then drive their vehicle back down to the trail head and wait for his dad and uncle.  When the dad and uncle did not show up, the son kept driving around to try and find his dad and uncle, but when he couldn't, he called 911.  SAR resources were called out and a search began.  Later on in the second day, one of the men hiked out to a road system and found by SAR.  The third man, the oldest of the three was still missing.  Additional resources were asked for from CORSAR counties to continue to search the rugged steep mountain area.  A request was sent to the Coast Guard to fly the area of drainage but the canopy was too thick to see hardly any of the area except for some of the south fork of the Sixes River itself.  SAR ground teams consisting of K-9, ATV, and ground searchers continued into the third day and located the last missing man in a drainage about a half mile away from their drop off point and were able to assist the man to an area where he was airlifted by the Coast Guard out of the area and to a nearby hospital.

75 year old, diabetic, male was walking forested property and never returned.  Caller advised that MP had missed breakfast and could not well in the first place.  Last seen about 2 hours prior to call.  Subject was located coming out of the brush onto trail by search personnel.  MP's blood sugar was at 30.

Male subject was visiting Ashland with parents when he wandered off un-escorted.  Parents were unable to locate him and reported him as missing to Ashland Police Department, due to the fact that the subject suffers from Dementia and requires constant care and monitoring.  Ashland Police Department requested the assistance of Jackson County Search and Rescue and Ashland's CERT Team (Community Emergency Response Team) to assist in the search.  A ground search was initiated and missing person flyers were distributed in the city.  The subject was located walking along the highway by two Medford Mail Tribune reporters en route to Soda Mountain on a un-related news story.  The reporters had received a copy of the missing person flyer from Search and Rescue less than fifteen minutes prior to locating the subject, and recognized him on the basis of the missing person flyer.  The subject returned with the reporters to the CP and was re-untied with his parents without further incident.  A complete de-brief of the subject was not available due to the fact that the subject is verbally non-responsive.  13.5 hours.

Subject was last seen in bed by the caregiver at 2330 hours on 6/16/10.  She woke to find him gone at about 0730 on 6/17/10.  Deputies were called to a missing person immediately.  SAR was not notified of a missing person until about 1400 hours.  The neighborhood was searched on ground and by deputies in vehicles.  An attempt to locate was sent out to the local public transportation and police agencies.  The subject was located by Portland Police near the Rose Quarter.  He was in good health and was reported to be trying to find a ride to California, where he thought his daughter was moving.  Total distance travelled from IPP was 9.2 miles.  Subject used Public transportation.

Locate a dementia walk away.  He was assisted by persons at the Safeway Store in Cottage Grove.  They brought him home after noticing he appeared confused and disoriented.  He does not know how he got to Safeway.

Subject frequently goes out for walks on his property.  He left at about 1130 hours and the family reported him missing at 1357 hours.  Patrol deputies along with Project lifesaver was deployed on scene.  When the subject was not located within an hour, a request for a K9 search team was requested.  NORSAR deployed one (1) bloodhound who located the subject about ? mile from his residence walking on a path.

On 1-31-10 at 2040 hours 911 was called for a missing Dementia male that was last seen by his care giver in his drive way by his house at 1400 but was not seen after that and the care giver did not know what the direction of travel was.  The missing subject was wearing rubber boots, hoody sweat shirt, and jeans.  The low temperature was forecasted for 35 deg. and clear for the evening.  The subject was fit and walks cross country 4-5 miles a day with his care giver.  A command post was set up and recourses were called and sent into the field.  The area was wooded and hilly and was primarily residents and private logging roads and to the North was USFS property.  At 0348 on 2-1-10 a search team found the missing subject down the road from his house and the subject had just walked out of the woods.  I talked to the subject and asked him if he knew what time it was or if he knew where he had gone and the subject told me he was not sure of either, He said "I just went for a walk and might have gone farther than I thought".  The subject was checked by the medics on scene and was ok.  I talked to the care giver about a tracking system device and I thought his family should be notified so the subject would not wonder any more with out knowing where he was.

MCSO SAR was contacted by PPB to assist with an endangered missing elderly person who had walked away from his vehicle after acting strangely.  Police Officers, Search One K9, MCSO SAR and a Detective searched several locations and eventually found subject at his residence about 2.6 miles from the Point Last Seen.  There was a "sighting" in the area of the PLS at 1700 hours.  The residence was checked at 1600 hours and again at 2035 hours when he was found.  The subject was significantly off his medications and was transported code 3 to the hospital to be stabilized.
[See report for details.]

On 07/02/10 at about 0830 hrs, I received a Missing Person Incident Report from DS J. Jahn.  Information received indicated that a 65 year old male subject had "walked away" from a care facility at in Cottage Grove.  Information found that the subject was last observed walking toward Cottage Grove to go and purchase beer.  The male subject was not allowed to purchase beer or leave the residence.  I responded to the address and made contact with a care giver, the care giver gave a brief description of the incident and advised that the subject has been diagnosed with Alzheimer's Disease.  I made attempts to contact possible involved persons or relatives and was not successful.  A possible witness was contacted who advised they had observed a male subject walking north on Interstate 5, the witness advised the male subject had the same body style and mannerisms that the missing subject possesses.  The witness also stated the observed male possessed the same limp as the missing subject.  She did not stop and make contact.  On 07/07/10, I returned from days off and discovered the missing subject had been located in the City of Salem by an Oregon State Trooper.  I made numerous attempts to contact the caregiver and the O.S.P trooper for status of the subject, I was not successful in speaking to any involved persons.
[See report for details.]
[See report for details.]
[See report for details.]

Subject reported finding human remains in a newly cleared field in Molalla.  Molalla Police as well as the medical examiner responded and found the subject.  Due to her location and clothing description she was believed to be [subject] who had been an Alzheimer's walk away in July, 2007.  Her body was taken to the medical examiners office where she was positively identified as [subject].  This narrative is to close-out the suspended case from 2007.  When I spoke with OERS they were not readily able to look up the previous OERS number associated with the search. [Original mission 2007-1159]
A 76 year old male left his house to get the mail and wandered several miles away.  He was found at the Corvallis Library and taken home.

Called by City of Portland Police Bureau to assist them in searching for a missing elderly male diagnosed with Alzheimer's.  The subject was found when he wandered into a bank and asked for help, left before employees could detain him, but was found shortly thereafter by Portland Police a few blocks from that bank.  He was uninjured.

78 yo male with Alzheimer's left son's residence in Aloha.  Male recently moved into son's house for 24hr. care.  Left around 2100 and was located in a motel nearby around 0230.  Subject may be a future Project Lifesaver client.  4 Sheriff SAR Team Paid and 2 Sheriff SAR Team volunteer.  8 Explorers, 4 radio operators and 4 jeep club volunteers.

On 10/1/10 at 1744 Deputy Wellborn, Oregon Project Lifesaver Coordinator and Yamhill County Sheriff's Office Project Lifesaver Deputy, contacted me via cell phone about a missing Project Lifesaver Client in Newberg.  I proceeded to notify other Project Lifesaver team members and YCSO deputies to assist.  I contact the caregiver and initiated an initial search towards the residence.  I also contact Newberg Police Dispatch to alert their officers. The dispatcher told me to contact YCOM as they had just transferred a 911 call about an elderly man near Newberg at a construction site and was confused. After contacting YCOM, I received the address and proceeded to the location.  Client was safe and talking to the man at the construction site. I returned him to his house and canceled any further support at 18:11 on 10/1/10.
[See report for details.]

On June 30th, 2010 Lincoln County SAR was called to locate a 79yo female who suffers from Dementia and Alzheimer's, that walked away from the house her son was working on.  79yo female was prone to walking away and just heading in any direction with no reason to why.  That day she had been walking around the yard and making laps around the yard of the house.  After the family did not see her come back around they got up and started looking in the house and yard.  After not finding her there they started walking around the neighborhood and asking people if they had seen her.  After a search by the family and neighbors, they contacted 911 and asked for assistance from SAR.  We arrived and researched the area and yards of homes with no luck.  Search was suspended that night and resumed the next morning.  After searching the area extensively, a person who lives in the area stated that he had seen someone matching the description of the missing female heading down to the end of his street.  He had not seen this person before but did recognize the clothing description given.  After sending 2 person team down into the area where he last saw her, the female was located in a small stream face up deceased.  The female's shoes were located in a tree stacked next to each other.  Her purse was located in the brush on the trail she took leading down to the water.  After taking photos we packaged up the female and removed from the scene.

Subject was visiting Family just outside of Yamhill for the weekend.  They went Blueberry picking early Monday morning and discovered Subject was missing at approx 06:30 AM.  They looked without success and contacted 911 at approx 10:40.  Sheriff's Office responded with Deputies, who ran roads and checked buildings close to the house where he was visiting.  SAR was contacted at approx 12:10 and the page went out at 12:40.  SAR was on site and set up with the Trailer at approx 14:00.  Tracker & assistant was in the field prior to trailer arrival, hasty teams were sent out shortly after arrival.  Three Deputies were tasked with Containment and the Sheriff's Office dog was in the field tracking unknown persons.  Life Flight was engaged to fly over and check the river East of the House and flew for 20 minutes.  Local Helicopter Special Deputy flew into the Search Area and landed 10 minutes after subject was located.  Subject was found on the side of the Road approx 15:10.  With his Granddaughter as an interpreter, he indicated he was thought he was in Mexico and was walking home.  Subject was checked by Paramedics and released.  Subject back with family within 30 minutes.
Stoneybrook Assisted living resident wandered away from the facility.  Returned by himself later and was found safe in his room.

MCSO SAR was contacted by PPB to assist with an endangered missing elderly person with dementia who had been missing for about 24 hours.  Police Officers, NorSAR K9, MCSO SAR and a Detective searched several locations throughout the City of Portland, and eventually found subject at NW 3rd and Couch in downtown Portland.  There were "sightings" in the area of the PLS at 1430 hours on 5/8 and in the St. John's neighborhood on at 1700 hrs. on 5/9.  The subject was found in good condition 'reliving' a part of his past as a homeless person 10 years earlier.

On 5/3/10 Portland Police Bureau Missing Person Detective Mike Weinstein requested MCSO Search and Rescue respond with an urban trailering air sent K9 to assist in locating a missing Alzheimer's elderly person.  I responded with the NORSAR K9 unit.  While en route PPB Police located the missing person at her former residence.

Overdue walker reported by daughter.  Subject 80 year old Japanese woman, speaks no English, in good health and dressed for environment.  Daughter reports "some short term memory loss" for which she takes a daily pill (unknown what the pill is).  SAR teams activated at the request of Corvallis Police Department and deployed in two-person vehicle teams to a possible sighting as a result of an "A Child is Missing" broadcast.  Subject located 2.36 (straight line) miles from residence after having likely walked nearly six miles.  Subject in good condition and was reportedly observed out walking alone again the morning after this incident.

On 02/25/10 at about 1345 hrs, an 82 year old man walked away from his residence in Milwaukie.  Milwaukie Police notified our agency.  Several units conducted a search of the area for the dementia patient.  He was found about an hour later by a unit searching for the man.

Subject was visiting Ashland with his wife from Canada.  They walked from their B & B to the theatres where they separated to watch two different plays.  Subject was directed by his wife to return to the B & B on foot at the end of the play.  Wife reported seeing subject enter the theatre, and reported him missing after he failed to return to the B & B at the end of the plays.  Subject was recovered due to a citizen call into 911 reporting an intoxicated male at the side of the roadway.  Ashland PD responded and found subject.  Subject was located with minor to moderate scrapes and cuts on his elbows, knees, and his head, indicating numerous falls during the night.  He was unable to orient himself, stating that he was in Canada.  When informed that he was in Ashland, Oregon he stated that he was going to visit Ashland soon, then corrected himself and said that he had just returned from Ashland.  Wife had reported that the subject suffered from mild dementia.  Subject was transported to Ashland Community Hospital for evaluation and then released to his wife.  7 hours

Call out for a missing dementia subject who wondered from his residence.  He was located about 200 feet from the house, downhill just off the road way next to a creek in his boxer type underwear and nothing else.

On 06/16/10 at about 1452 hrs, the Lane County Sheriffs Office received a Missing Person complaint from Sherwood Foster Care in Veneta, an 84 year old Alzheimer patient had walked away from the location; the patient's destination was not known.  I learned the missing person is a Project Life Saver recipient and is currently fitted with a tracking bracelet that is monitored through Lane County Search and Rescue.  LCSO SAR Manager Nick Wedmore responded to assist.  LCSO Deputy M. Nelson responded to assist, at about 1506, it was reported that [subject] had been located by Sherwood Foster Care staff.  She had been wandering toward Territorial Hwy, she had been contacted and safely returned to the care facility without further incident.

On 03-11-10 Portland Police requested the assistance of Search and Rescue personnel to assist in locating an 88 year old with dementia that never arrived home.  Before arriving on scene the elderly subject was located as an unwanted trying to get into a house 60 blocks away.

88 year old male when missing from residence.  He was located by a neighbor to the west and over a hill.  Direction of travel was in line with house and chicken coop that he went out to inspect.  He was located in an upright position kind of shuffling through the brush off trail.

On May 6, 2010 (Thur) at about 1227 hrs, Beaverton PD officers responded to a 89 year old male missing person with Dementia and who is a Project Lifesaver client.  The client lives at Beaverton Hills Assistant Living in Beaverton, OR and this was the IPP.  At about 1240 hrs, WCSO Cpl. Trost and I responded from WCSO with Project Lifesaver tracking equipment.  At 1252 hrs, Officer Henderson or Ofc Crosslin with Beaverton PD located the subject inside Target business while conducting an hasty search.  The subject was in fine condition.  We obtained a electronic signal from the transmitter just as the subject was found and we were about  mile from the find location before getting a signal.  Refer to Beaverton PD report 10-2951 for more info.
30 SAR Volunteers responded to search for a 61 year old, insulin dependant diabetic male that wandered away Bend's North end Burger King.  OSP located the male on I-5 in Salem.
77 year old walked away from his home and was reported as missing by his wife.  He was found by Sgt. Stephens on Borden Rd and returned to his home.

On 01/15/2011 at about 1255 hours it was reported to 911 Dispatch that Carolyn Singleton was missing from the Johnson Creek Fred Meyers in Portland after she had been dropped off to go shopping with a gift card.  According to the call, Ms. Singleton suffered from dementia and schizophrenia and it was unknown where she went.  I arrived with one other Deputy Sheriff in the area and we began to check the area she was last known to be in.  I placed a call to her daughter to obtain information for the Lost Person Questionnaire and while on the phone with her, she told me that her mother had returned home by apparently taking the bus and failed to tell anyone.
Locate a walkaway dementia subject from a residence.  He was in the field behind the house.  3rd time for this subject

On 02/05/11 at 1951 hrs, [reporting party] reported that her husband Ivan left his residence located for a walk.  [reporting party] stated he was angry for some unknown reason.  [reporting party] stated that Ivan has Dementia/Alzheimer's and it has been increasingly getting worse.  [reporting party] stated that Ivan is normally gone for 15 to 30 minutes when he leaves.  [reporting party] stated when Ivan did not return after thirty minutes, she decided to call family and the police.  Six officers responded and began searching the roads in the area.  Two SAR coordinators began the missing person forms and call outs.  Three coordinators were called out to begin an urgent rural search.  2123 hrs., Ivan was located .81 miles from his.  Ivan was unable to say his address but stated his name.  Ivan told the person who found him he was looking for his wife.  Ivan's Identity was confirmed by a Washington County Deputy.  Ivan was returned to his residence in good condition.  The family was given information on Project Lifesaver

On 02/08/11 at about 1329 Hrs, LCSO Deputies were dispatched to the address of 26901 Pickens Road in regards to a possible Alzheimers Patient walk-away from a care facility there.  While in route to the area, Deputies began a patrol of Cantrell Road, Pickens Road and Central Road.  Deputies successfully located the Missing Person on Cantrell Road at mile post 3, the subject was in good condition and was not injured; the subject was transported back to the listed facility without incident.  The subject, identified as Donald Eugene Clark, was disorientated and he did not know where he was.  Clark also advised that he did not know what his destination was and did not know where he was going.

[Subject] was reported missing from his residence.  He has Alzheimer's.  Family had been looking for him for 2 hours to no avail.  SAR Lt. and deputies deployed to scene.  On the way to the residence, SAR Lt. saw a subject walking with a dog southbound down I-5.  He needed to turn around to get to the subject, and OSP had already stopped him.  The subject was [Subject] and his dog.  Lt. Rowland transported subject and dog to his residence.  Stand Down.  1 hour

On February 17, 2011 WCSO SAR were called to assist Tigard Police Department with a missing Project Lifesaver client. Asked by Gresham Police to assist in searching for a 96 year old missing woman diagnosed with Dementia.  She was located at a local hospital and had been found earlier in the morning by a newspaper deliverer who called an ambulance.

Subject walked away from an assisted living facility and was located by LE on Main St of Eagle Point.  SAR was stood down.  1.25 Hours

At about 0910 hrs, a 79 year old male was reported missing as a Alzheimer/Dementia subject from his residence near Sherwood, OR.  A patrol deputy responded to the scene, checking the residence and gathering information while WCSO SAR coordinator responded by calling for additional resources to the scene.  Area checks with local hospitals and roads were checked.  At about 1039 hrs, [subject] was found by a neighbor about 1/4 mile from his residence and returned home safely.  [subject] family was given information about Project Lifesaver.

Female with dementia was told by her husband to wait for his return.  While he was gone, she wandered off.  She was found 2 days later alive.  BLM & US Forest Service assisted with a large number of searchers.

A 93 year old man walked away from his travel trailer where he was living.  Family reported that they had seen the subject at 4:30 pm and noticed he was missing from his trailer about 8:30 pm.  Neighbors looked around for awhile and then called the Sheriff's office.  Deputies responded to the location and assisted in searching for the missing man.  It was a still quite warm night and the missing subject was dressed warmly.  The subject had never wandered off before and was not very steady on his feet.  All surrounding residences and yards were searched and a search plan was formulated for the following morning, due to heavy brush and the fact the missing subject was very hard of hearing.  Following morning, search members were en route to the location when notified that the missing subject had been located.  Law enforcement was on scene and determined that the subject had walked out onto the highway, took the next driveway back behind a house and got tangled up in some brush where he fell asleep.  A family friend found the missing man when the subject yelled out.  The missing man was only about 100 feet from his residence but had to walk about 600 feet to get to his location due to the heavy brush.  The missing subject was somewhat hypothermic and was treated on scene by ambulance crew.

Dispatched for a missing person call.  [Subject] who has Alzheimer's had walked away from his residence and couldn't be located by his wife.  Neighbor found Tom and returned him to his residence as deputy was arriving.
Search for missing 92 yo female with dementia.  Subject was located by K9s near her home wrapped in blackberry bushes.
Search for missing Alzheimer's male subj.  Found by neighbors when he knocked on their window.

The subject, described by acquaintances as a "hermit," had not been seen in town or around his place for around a week (unknown exactly).  One acquaintance drives by the place regularly and stopped to see if the subject was around on 9/8.  He found the gate unlocked but did not see the subject.  Upon reflection, he went back on 9/9 to investigate further and found the cabin unlocked and no one there.  The condition of things made him suspicious that something had happened to the subject.  SAR responded to search the 120 acre property with the help of 2 cadaver dogs and handlers from Wallowa County.  One dog team started from where ground SAR had detected an odor and quickly located the deceased subject.

On 09/09/2011 at about 1249 hours the Clackamas County Sheriffs Office was advised of a subject with Alzheimer's missing from the address 32395 SW Arbor Lake Drive.  Patrol units responded to the area and started searching roads in the area.  Call-outs were made to volunteer resources and at 1331 hours the missing subject was returned home safely by her neighbor.

WCSO deputies responded to a missing 87 year old female who suffers Alzheimer's and was last seen at home at [address].  They performed an area check and searched the property.  At 1930 hrs, WCSO SAR was requested to respond and two overhead team members responded to the scene.  Patrol and Hillsboro Police K9 began a track for Anna.  After about one hour, Anna was located, she had gone about 1000 feet from her residence, fell to the ground, rolled into a tree and was injured.  At 2123 hrs, SAR arrived on scene, helped backboard and litter her out to waiting ambulance.  Anna was treated at the hospital for a broken neck and hip.  Anna was later entered into Project Lifesaver program.

Missing person was staying in a health care facility when he walked away.  Missing person was suffering from dementia and had some other health related issues.  A search wqs initiated by Eugene Police and requested our assistance in locating the missing person.  Missing person was located in the downtown area of Eugene on 10-21-2011 by local officers.

On October 28th 2011 I received Information of a missing person near Myrtle Point Oregon.  I went to that location with other officers to attempt to locate the missing person.  At the time we did not know if the person was missing under suspicious circumstances so we did a two pronged approach to the search, treating it as if it was a major crime as well as a missing person.  The major crimes portion was headed up by Detective Sergeant Dan Looney.  I headed up the search and rescue effort.  On the first day we had twelve SAR personnel respond.  They searched the area around the residence where it was likely the missing person would be located.  That area is a square grassy, hilly, open area consisting of about five acres that is used for farming sheep and other agricultural purposes.  It is surrounded by timber on three sides and bordered by a gravel road.  The search consisted of a grid ground search with approximately 6 feet between searchers.  We used the gravel road as the start of our search and the timber to border the end and edges.  Additionally a dog team searched several likely areas where we suspected the subject might go.  Nothing of interest was located on the first day and the search was suspended for the evening do to safety concerns.  On the second day we again had twelve SAR personnel.  We analyzed our search patterns of the first day and identified several areas that needed to be more thoroughly searched.  These were some dense brushy areas within the grid search area and locations where it was likely the victim would have gone to care for her animals.  There were several areas identified by the dog team that needed to be covered more thoroughly.  Based on this discussion, assignments were made, and the search began at approximately 0830.  At 0907 the dog team radioed in they had made voice contact with the missing person.  This was approximately one half mile from the residence, up hill, in the timber.  It was confirmed that the voice contact was that of our missing person.  Numerous Deputies and EMS responded to her location.  They found her conscious alert and talkative.  Her condition was described as hypothermic and suffering from exposure to the elements.  At the time that she was located it was raining lightly.  During the two days that she been in the woods prior to being located it had been very cold and had frozen each morning.  The victim was removed by EMS and transported to Coquille Valley Hospital where she was treated.  She was later release from the hospital but had to return one day later due to complications from the exposure.  It should be noted that preliminary information from friends and acquaintances painted a picture of a frail woman who would not walk far.  Later information from contractors who worked on the property leads us to believe that Suzie probably gets around quite well (although with a walking stick or cane).  She was fond of mushrooms and mushroom picking and was equipped for that activity when located.

On 11/09/2011 at about 1316 hours [reporting party] contacted CCSO Dispatch to report that his wife was missing from their residence in Charbonneau. We conducted a search of all the roads in Charbonneau and learned [subject] had been given a golf cart at the golf course.  A private citizen found her and returned her to her home, unharmed.

On November 14, 2011 at approximately 11:21 pm hours the reporting party realized his wife was missing.  He stated she was 76 years old and had dementia and had previously stated she wanted to go to California.  Lake County Sheriff's Office and Lake County Search and Rescue were activated.  At approximately 1:08 am on November 15, 2011, Lake County Sheriff's Deputy Luke Campbell located the missing subject near an abandoned house in the burrow ditch, approximately 6 miles south of her residence.  The missing subject had blood on her face and was transported by the Lakeview Disaster Unit to Lake District Hospital where she was treated.

Female with Alzheimer's walked away from her home at about 0320 hrs.  Husband heard a click at that time but did not get up as he thought it was his wife going to the bathroom like she does every morning.  Husband awoke and could not locate her and started his own search at about 0500 hrs.  SAR and Yachats Fire Personnel arrived on scene and started searching the area. Subject also had put on a sweatshirt and pants, and was not wearing the nightgown.

On 12/20/11 SAR coordinator T. Morris responded to the above location for a missing Alzheimer's patient that left his family home in Aloha, OR around 1530.  He advised through a note he was going for a walk and never returned.  He was reported missing around 2100.  He was later located at a nearby Bar around 2345.
